    {
      "id": "24fb7d4dc4786ecaea38a26b415038c9a53e654a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 136,
        "name": "Alexey Lyashkov",
        "email": "alexey.lyashkov@hpe.com",
        "username": "shadow"
      },
      "date": "2013-10-16 08:31:53.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 9: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nplease don't kill existent reimplenetation - but move it's into some private header to ability to use on platforms without hlist and list native implementation.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 9
    },
    {
      "id": "e401e5e44fecbf1419302d79d3f5df0a21eaf450",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 136,
        "name": "Alexey Lyashkov",
        "email": "alexey.lyashkov@hpe.com",
        "username": "shadow"
      },
      "date": "2013-10-16 08:37:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 9:\n\nHm.. i don't like that change at all.\n\nthat patch introduce an conflict with POSIX sys/queue.h implementation.\nchanges in libcfs/include/libcfs/darwin/darwin-sync.h - wrong,\nchanges in libsysio prent that code to be POSIX safe.\n\nplease don't introduce any conflicts with POSIX.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 9
    },
    {
      "id": "b6de593292303d8bd810beeef6db9f82a0f81323",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 136,
        "name": "Alexey Lyashkov",
        "email": "alexey.lyashkov@hpe.com",
        "username": "shadow"
      },
      "date": "2013-10-16 09:06:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 9: (1 inline comment)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 9
    },
    {
      "id": "04645ee0ad2b8ee5fed0969e44a80b68ff7f2356",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2013-10-16 15:46:58.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 9:\n\nHm. So the problem is a LIST_HEAD macro conflict. Since for the linux kernel it is defined as\n\n#define LIST_HEAD(name) \\\n        struct list_head name = LIST_HEAD_INIT(name)\n\nI can expand that out so to avoid a conflict. With that resolved we can then use LIST_HEAD directly from posix/queue.h",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 9
    },
    {
      "id": "f28473c0ebb6cf304986883dd79bf383ab59452f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 136,
        "name": "Alexey Lyashkov",
        "email": "alexey.lyashkov@hpe.com",
        "username": "shadow"
      },
      "date": "2013-10-16 18:21:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 9:\n\nI don't sure about replace an using LIST_HEAD in static macro init, without dirty hack like you add in patch.\nif you worry about libcfs/list.h - you need expand all structure initialization in separate patch to avoid using any LIST_HEAD macros at all.\n\ni suggest to divide a patch to three parts - hlist_head replacement (with creating an hlist implementation for platforms other when linux) because it's don't exist on other platform, expand an structure initialization to avoid using LIST_HEAD macro and patch to replace an list_* functions with linux implementation - with creating an replacement for other platforms.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 9
    },
    {
      "id": "f88b5ac87aef13f1eb776bcd098826ff08cf58be",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-11-05 00:11:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 9: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nJames, any chance you could restructure this patch in a similar manner to the cfs_atomic_* changes, so that the core code allows use of Linux list_*() and struct list_head, but the thousands of \"convert Lustre code\" changes are split into many smaller patches?\n\nGetting this landed in one shot is almost impossible without conflict or blocking other patches landing for days.  Also, new patches can't be changed to use list_*() until the first part of the patch lands.  After that, I could ask new patches to use the Linux primitives while the rest of the conversion patches make their way through the system.  That avoids moving backward with other changes/additions to the code.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 9
    },
    {
      "id": "8f6f40b47597cfd8c9ba67830a77451a34338c7c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2013-11-05 16:28:34.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 9:\n\nSure I can break this patch up.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 9
    },
    {
      "id": "2a4ef6fd2bdcb1c57938f06259b79314ab99a9c5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
